# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: kicad-eda
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:kicad-eda/comparison-of-eda-software] This page is a comparison of electronic design automation (EDA) software which is used today to design the near totality of electronic devices.
[src:kicad-eda/comparison-of-eda-software] Modern electronic devices are too complex to be designed without the help of a computer.
[src:kicad-eda/comparison-of-eda-software] Electronic devices may consist of integrated circuits (ICs), integrated circuit substrates, printed circuit boards (PCBs), field-programmable gate arrays (FPGAs) or a combination of them.
[src:kicad-eda/comparison-of-eda-software] Integrated circuits may consist of a combination of digital and analog circuits.
[src:kicad-eda/comparison-of-eda-software] These circuits can contain a combination of transistors, resistors, capacitors or specialized components such as analog neural networks, antennas or fuses.
[src:kicad-eda/comparison-of-eda-software] The design of each of these electronic devices generally proceeds from a high- to a low-level of abstraction.
[src:kicad-eda/comparison-of-eda-software] For FPGAs the low-level description consists of a binary file to be flashed into the gate array, while for an integrated circuit or printed circuit board the low-level description consists of a layout file which describes the masks to be used for lithography inside a foundry.
[src:kicad-eda/comparison-of-eda-software] Each design step requires specialized tools, and many of these tools can be used for designing multiple types of electronic circuits.
[src:kicad-eda/comparison-of-eda-software] For example, a program for high-level digital synthesis can usually be used both for IC digital design as well as for programming an FPGA.
[src:kicad-eda/comparison-of-eda-software] Similarly, a tool for schematic-capture and analog simulation can generally be used both for analog IC design and for PCB design.
[src:kicad-eda/comparison-of-eda-software] In the case of integrated circuits (ICs) for example, a single chip may contain today more than 20 billion transistors and, as a general rule, every single transistor in a chip must work as intended.
[src:kicad-eda/comparison-of-eda-software] Since a single VLSI mask set can cost up to 10-100 millions, trial and error approaches are not economically viable.
[src:kicad-eda/comparison-of-eda-software] To minimize the risk of any design mistakes, the design flow is heavily automated.
[src:kicad-eda/comparison-of-eda-software] EDA software assists the designer in every step of the design process and every design step is accompanied by heavy test phases.
[src:kicad-eda/comparison-of-eda-software] Errors may be present in the high-level code already, such as for the Pentium FDIV floating-point unit bug, or it can be inserted all the way down to physical synthesis, such as a missing wire, or a timing violation.
[src:kicad-eda/comparison-of-eda-software] These vendors offer software bundles which allow to cover the full spectrum of IC design, from HDL synthesis to physical synthesis and verification.
[src:kicad-eda/comparison-of-eda-software] The development of EDA software for IC design is tightly connected with the development of technology nodes.
[src:kicad-eda/comparison-of-eda-software] The properties of a specific semiconductor foundry, such as the transistor models, the physical characteristics and the design rules, are usually encoded in file formats which are proprietary to one or more EDA vendors.
[src:kicad-eda/comparison-of-eda-software] This set of files constitutes the process design kit (PDK) and it is usually developed as a joint effort between the foundry and an EDA vendor.
[src:kicad-eda/comparison-of-eda-software] Foundries therefore usually release PDKs which are compatible only for one specific EDA bundle.
[src:kicad-eda/comparison-of-eda-software] The information contained inside PDKs is usually considered confidential.
[src:kicad-eda/comparison-of-eda-software] PDKs are therefore usually protected by non disclosure agreements (NDAs) and may be shipped in an incomplete or in an encrypted form to the designers.
[src:kicad-eda/comparison-of-eda-software] Of these, LTSpice, TINA-TI, Micro-cap are free proprietary applications based on SPICE.
[src:kicad-eda/comparison-of-eda-software] Micro-Cap was released as freeware in July 2019, when its parent company Spectrum Software closed down while LTSpice has been free for a long time.
[src:kicad-eda/comparison-of-eda-software] PDF, PNG, SVG, JSON, Gerber, Excellon, Pick and Place CSV file, CSV-formatted drill chart, Bill of Materials CSV file, Altium netlist, FreePCB netlist, PADS Layout Netlist, Spice netlist.
[src:kicad-eda/comparison-of-eda-software] EAGLE/KiCad libraries, Altium/Allegro Schematics, DXF, SVG, STEP, etc.
[src:kicad-eda/comparison-of-eda-software] Gerber, IPC-2581C, ODB++, EDIF netlists, D356 netlists, JEP30, Pick and Place CSV file, CSV-formatted drill chart, Bill of Materials CSV file.
[src:kicad-eda/comparison-of-eda-software] PDF, Gerber, GerberX2, Excellon, ODB++, DXF, IDF, PKP, testpoint file, metafile, BMP.
[src:kicad-eda/comparison-of-eda-software] Free and open-source (FOSS) EDA software bundles are currently under fast development mainly thanks to the DARPA and Google's openROAD project.
[src:kicad-eda/comparison-of-eda-software] The OpenROAD project offers a complete stack of tools from high-level synthesis down to layout generation The flow includes Yosys for logic synthesis, OpenLane for physical synthesis and targets the SkyWater 130 nm PDK.
[src:kicad-eda/comparison-of-eda-software] The flow is currently utilized to submit design for free fabrication at Google.
[src:kicad-eda/comparison-of-eda-software] High-level synthesis software can generally be used for the design of both application-specific integrated circuits (ASICs) and field-programmable gate arrays (FPGAs).
[src:kicad-eda/comparison-of-eda-software] Most high-level synthesis software is used to edit and verify code written in one of the mainstream hardware description languages (HDL) like VHDL or Verilog.
[src:kicad-eda/comparison-of-eda-software] Other tools instead operate at a higher level of abstraction and allow to synthesize HDL code starting from languages like Chisel or SpinalHDL.
[src:kicad-eda/comparison-of-eda-software] The higher abstraction of such languages enables formal verification of HDL code.
[src:kicad-eda/comparison-of-eda-software] This list does not include schematic editors or simulators since these can generally be used both for Integrated Circuits (ICs) and for Printed Circuit Board (PCB) as long as device models are available.
[src:kicad-eda/electronic-design-automation] The earliest electronic design automation is attributed to IBM with the documentation of its 700 series computers in the 1950s.
[src:kicad-eda/electronic-design-automation] IBM has developed one of the earliest computer-aided design (CAD) systems, known as Automated Logic Diagram (ALD), which was originally executed on the IBM 704 and 705 mainframe computers.
[src:kicad-eda/electronic-design-automation] The design process started with engineers manually drafting logic schematics, which were later transcribed onto standardized templates and converted into punch cards for digital processing.
[src:kicad-eda/electronic-design-automation] Although focused on mechanical geometry, General Motors’ DAC-1, built jointly with IBM, was among the earliest interactive, graphics-driven CAD systems and proved the practicality of screen-based editing for complex engineering data, an idea adopted by IC layout tools.
[src:kicad-eda/electronic-design-automation] Prior to the development of EDA, integrated circuits were designed by hand and manually laid out.
[src:kicad-eda/electronic-design-automation] Some advanced shops used geometric software to generate tapes for a Gerber photoplotter, responsible for generating a monochromatic exposure image, but even those copied digital recordings of mechanically drawn components.
[src:kicad-eda/electronic-design-automation] The process was fundamentally graphic, with the translation from electronics to graphics done manually; the best-known company from this era was Calma, whose GDSII format is still in use today.
[src:kicad-eda/electronic-design-automation] In the early 1970s, developers started to automate circuit design in addition to drafting and the first placement and routing tools were developed.
[src:kicad-eda/electronic-design-automation] Because of the Cold War, developments often occurred in near parallel.
[src:kicad-eda/electronic-design-automation] In the Western world, the proceedings of the IEEE and the Design Automation Conference catalogued the large majority of the developments of the time, and by 1973 a large bibliography was needed to keep track of developments in the field.
[src:kicad-eda/electronic-design-automation] In the Soviet Union, progress was largely described in a series of books, starting in 1975.
[src:kicad-eda/electronic-design-automation] Calma’s Graphic Design System (GDS, 1971) and its 32-bit successor GDSII (1978) let engineers digitise and edit full-chip layouts on minicomputers; the accompanying GDSII Stream file became the de-facto mask exchange standard and is still recognised in modern design flows.
[src:kicad-eda/electronic-design-automation] The next era began following the publication of "Introduction to VLSI Systems" by Carver Mead and Lynn Conway in 1980, and is considered the standard textbook for chip design.
[src:kicad-eda/electronic-design-automation] The result was an increase in the complexity of the chips that could be designed, with improved access to design verification tools that used logic simulation.
[src:kicad-eda/electronic-design-automation] The chips were easier to lay out and more likely to function correctly, since their designs could be simulated more thoroughly prior to construction.
[src:kicad-eda/electronic-design-automation] Although the languages and tools have evolved, this general approach of specifying the desired behavior in a textual programming language and letting the tools derive the detailed physical design remains the basis of digital IC design today.
[src:kicad-eda/electronic-design-automation] The earliest EDA tools were produced academically.
[src:kicad-eda/electronic-design-automation] One of the most famous was the "Berkeley VLSI Tools Tarball", a set of UNIX utilities used to design early VLSI systems.
[src:kicad-eda/electronic-design-automation] Widely used were the Espresso heuristic logic minimizer, responsible for circuit complexity reductions and Magic, a computer-aided design platform.
[src:kicad-eda/electronic-design-automation] Another crucial development was the formation of MOSIS, a consortium of universities and fabricators that developed an inexpensive way to train student chip designers by producing real integrated circuits.
[src:kicad-eda/electronic-design-automation] The basic concept was to use reliable, low-cost, relatively low-technology IC processes and pack a large number of projects per wafer, with several copies of chips from each project remaining preserved.
[src:kicad-eda/electronic-design-automation] Cooperating fabricators either donated the processed wafers or sold them at cost, as they saw the program as helpful to their own long-term growth.
[src:kicad-eda/electronic-design-automation] 1981 marked the beginning of EDA as an industry.
[src:kicad-eda/electronic-design-automation] For many years, the larger electronic companies, such as Hewlett-Packard, Tektronix and Intel, had pursued EDA internally, with managers and developers beginning to spin out of these companies to concentrate on EDA as a business.
[src:kicad-eda/electronic-design-automation] Daisy Systems, Mentor Graphics and Valid Logic Systems were all founded around this time and collectively referred to as DMV.
[src:kicad-eda/electronic-design-automation] Department of Defense additionally began funding of VHDL as a hardware description language.
[src:kicad-eda/electronic-design-automation] Within a few years, there were many companies specializing in EDA, each with a slightly different emphasis.
[src:kicad-eda/electronic-design-automation] The first trade show for EDA was held at the Design Automation Conference in 1984, and in 1986, Verilog, another popular high-level design language, was first introduced as a hardware description language by Gateway Design Automation.
[src:kicad-eda/electronic-design-automation] Simulators quickly followed these introductions, permitting direct simulation of chip designs and executable specifications.
[src:kicad-eda/electronic-design-automation] Within several years, back-ends were developed to perform logic synthesis.
[src:kicad-eda/electronic-design-automation] Current digital flows are extremely modular, with front ends producing standardized design descriptions that compile into invocations of units similar to cells without regard to their individual technology.
[src:kicad-eda/electronic-design-automation] Cells implement logic or other electronic functions via the utilisation of a particular integrated circuit technology.
[src:kicad-eda/electronic-design-automation] Fabricators generally provide libraries of components for their production processes, with simulation models that fit standard simulation tools.
[src:kicad-eda/electronic-design-automation] Most analog circuits are still designed in a manual fashion, requiring specialist knowledge that is unique to analog design (such as matching concepts).
[src:kicad-eda/electronic-design-automation] Hence, analog EDA tools are far less modular, since many more functions are required, they interact more strongly and the components are, in general, less ideal.
[src:kicad-eda/electronic-design-automation] EDA for electronics has rapidly increased in importance with the continuous scaling of semiconductor technology.
[src:kicad-eda/electronic-design-automation] Some users are foundry operators, who operate the semiconductor fabrication facilities ("fabs") and additional individuals responsible for utilising the technology design-service companies who use EDA software to evaluate an incoming design for manufacturing readiness.
[src:kicad-eda/electronic-design-automation] EDA tools are also used for programming design functionality into FPGAs or field-programmable gate arrays, customisable integrated circuit designs.
[src:kicad-eda/electronic-design-automation] Synopsys announced a planned acquisition of Ansys in 2024, but Ansys remains an independent, publicly traded company until the deal closes (expected H1 2025).
[src:kicad-eda/electronic-design-automation] Many EDA companies acquire small companies with software or other technology that can be adapted to their core business.
[src:kicad-eda/electronic-design-automation] This is happening due to a trend to place entire electronic systems on a single chip.
[src:kicad-eda/electronic-design-automation] Machine-learning methods are now applied at every major stage of the integrated-circuit design flow, from high-level synthesis through sign-off.
[src:kicad-eda/electronic-design-automation] Machine-learning shortens turnaround times and improves power, performance and area (PPA).
[src:kicad-eda/electronic-design-automation] EDA vendors have since integrated similar optimization engines into production toolchains.
[src:kicad-eda/electronic-design-automation] The OpenROAD Project (Foundations and Realisation of Open, Accessible Design), launched under DARPA’s IDEA program, released a no-human-in-the-loop RTL-to-GDS flow that has successfully taped-out designs.
[src:kicad-eda/electronic-design-automation] Conferences such as ORConf and the annual FOSSi Foundation roadmap sessions now dedicate substantial tracks to open-source EDA progress.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] The **Gerber format** is an open, ASCII, vector format for printed circuit board (PCB) designs.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] It is the *de facto* standard used by PCB industry software to describe the printed circuit board images: copper layers, solder mask, legend, drill data, etc.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] The standard file extension is `.GBR` or `.gbr` though other extensions like `.GB`, `.geb` or `.gerber` are also used.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] It is documented by The Gerber Layer Format Specification and some related (but less universally supported) extensions such as XNC drill files and GerberJob to convey information about the entire PCB, as opposed to single layers.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] PCBs are designed on a specialized electronic design automation (EDA) or a computer-aided design (CAD) system.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] The CAD systems output PCB fabrication data to allow fabrication of the board.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] This data typically contains a Gerber file for each image layer (copper layers, solder mask, legend or silk...).
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] Gerber is also the standard image input format for all bare board fabrication equipment needing image data, such as photoplotters, legend printers, direct imagers or automated optical inspection (AOI) machines and for viewing reference images in different departments.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] For assembly the fabrication data contains the solder paste layers and the central locations of components to create the stencil and place and bond the components.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] The official website contains the specification, test files, notes and the Reference Gerber Viewer to support users and especially developers of Gerber software.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] The CAD systems then outputs PCB fabrication data to allow fabrication of the board.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] The fabricator loads them into a computer-aided manufacturing (CAM) system to prepare data for each step of the PCB production process.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] The .FileFunction attribute is the standardized method to link each layer in the PCB with its corresponding Gerber file in the fabrication data.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] If attributes are not supported, then only informal methods are available.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] A simple informal method is to express the file function clearly in the file name.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] Sometimes the file extension is abused to indicate the file function - e.g. .BOT for the bottom layer rather than the standard extension .GBR.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] In industry this is considered poor practice and engineers should use the appropriate X2 attribute instead.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] PCB Fabrication Data must comply with a number of rules: all layers must be aligned, a profile layer must be included, etc.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] The CAD netlist can be embedded in the Gerber files.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] However, for historic reasons, netlists often are described in a separate file in IPC-D-356A, an electrical test format.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] The material stack up, components and finishes are typically provided in informal text files or drawings.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] In 2018 Ucamco has published a specification for an extension of the Gerber format to cover this fabrication documentation.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] RS-274X, extended Gerber or X-Gerber, was originally released in September 1998.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] It consists of a stream of commands generating an ordered stream of graphics objects.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] The graphics objects can be positive or negative.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] Superimposed in the correct order they create the final image.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] A Gerber file contains the complete description of a PCB layer image without requiring any external files.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] It has all the imaging operators needed for a PCB image.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] Planes and pads can be specified without the need to paint or vector-fill as in Standard Gerber.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] Released in February 2014, Gerber X2 adds additional metadata to the image.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] Attributes allow adding metadata to a Gerber file.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] Attributes are akin to labels providing information associated with image files, or features within them.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] For more information about attributes see X2 FAQ or intro video in the external links.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] Fabrication documentation such as finish, overall thickness and materials is specified in a separate Gerber Job File.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] The format specification is published at the official website.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] It was already obsolete after the introduction of the much more capable Extended Gerber in 1998.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] Standard Gerber was a numerical control (NC) format designed by Gerber Systems Corp to drive their vector photo plotters for the PCB industry in the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] It was a subset of the Electronic Industries Association RS-274-D specification, a format to drive mechanical NC machines in a wide range of industries.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] It was widely used to drive vector plotters.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] Standard Gerber was a simple ASCII format consisting of commands and XY coordinates.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] A Standard Gerber is an NC standard but not an image description standard: essential image information such the coordinate unit and the *apertures* definitions are not standardized.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] (Apertures are the basic shapes, similar to fonts in a PDF file.) They are described in a free-format sidecar text file intended for human reading, called an *aperture file* or a *wheel file*.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] The sender and receiver have to agree on their meaning case-by-case.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] Standard Gerber supports only the simple imaging operators that a vector plotter is capable of - drawing tracks and flashing apertures.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] This is insufficient for efficient PCB fabrication data.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] Copper pours must be created by *painting* (aka *stroking* or *vector-filling*) them with a vast number of tracks.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] All but the simplest pads are also painted because of the cost creating a corresponding physical aperture.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] Painting creates the intended image but results in very large files that take long time to process and need error-prone manual work in CAM.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] (An aperture wheel is a rotating disk on which physical apertures are mounted, and by rotating the wheel the photoplotter selects the aperture to use.) Standard Gerber is not suitable for automated data transfer between PCB designers and manufacturers.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] The Gerber file format is named after Joseph Gerber, an entrepreneur and inventor who pioneered vector photoplotters.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] In 1980 Gerber Systems Corp. published the first edition of the *Gerber Format: a subset of EIA RS-274-D; plot data format reference book*, a subset of EIA RS-274-D it used to drive their line of vector photoplotters.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] This format became known as Standard Gerber and was adopted by several other photoplotter vendors.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] Standard Gerber became the de facto standard image format for PCB fabrication.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] In 1991 with the availability of the more capable raster photoplotters, the Gerber format was extended with polygon areas and "mass parameters".
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] These allow the user to dynamically define apertures of different shapes and sizes, as well as defining polygon area fills without the need for "painting".
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] It became a superset of RS-274-D standard Gerber.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] The impetus to develop mass parameters was provided by AT&T.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] This created a family of input formats, each one dedicated to a specific Gerber plotter model.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] In April 1998 Gerber Systems Corp. was taken over by Barco ETS, Barco's PCB division, which is now called Ucamco.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] In September 1998 Ucamco published the *RS-274X Format User's Guide*, a specification which unified the family of formats to a single image format, revoking a large number of model-specific constructs.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] The format became known as Extended Gerber or GerberX.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] Extended Gerber quickly superseded Standard Gerber as the *de facto* standard for PCB image data.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] This became the de facto image standard for the PCB industry.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] It is sometimes called "the backbone of the electronics industry".
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] In the course of 2012 the format was comprehensively reviewed in *the great reform*.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] A representative library of 10,000 files from all over the world was investigated to establish current practice.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] Constructs that were rarely or never used were deprecated.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] Constructs with unclear interpretations were clarified.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] The specification document was re-organized and its quality improved.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] This resulted in revision I1 to I4 of the specification, published from December 2012 on.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] The result was a simple, but powerful format, focused on the current needs of the PCB industry.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] This version of the Gerber format was developed by Karel Tavernier and Rik Breemeersch from Ucamco.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] In June 2013 Ucamco published a proposal to add three new commands to the Gerber format which allow inclusion of image attributes conveying metadata attached to the image and its components.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] It invited feedback from the Gerber users before committing these ideas to a firm specification.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] This process resulted in revision J1 in February 2014, updated with further revisions until revision 2015.07.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] Including metadata adds intelligence to the format.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] It converts a mere image description format to a full-fledged PCB data transfer format.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] This is called *the second extension* and results what is known as *Gerber X2*, Gerber X1 being the pure image format.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] Gerber X2 is fully backward compatible with X1, as the attributes do not affect the image.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] Gerber X2 was developed by Karel Tavernier, Ludek Brukner and Thomas Weyn.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] In September 2014 Ucamco revoked Standard Gerber.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] In August 2015 Ucamco published a draft specification adding nested step and repeat and block apertures to make panel descriptions more efficient, calling for comments from the user community.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] The final specification was published in November 2016 after substantial input.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] This revision was developed by Karel Tavernier and Rik Breemeersch.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] Shortly afterwards the Cuprum Gerber viewer developed the first implementation.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] In July 2016 Ucamco published a draft specification to include netlist information in Gerber, calling for input from the user community.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] After a number of revisions of the draft triggered by input from users, the draft was finalized on 2 October 2016.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] In March 2017 Ucamco published a draft specification to include fabrication documentation in Gerber calling for input from the user community.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] There was a lively discussion, the draft went through seven public revisions before being finalized early April 2018.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] In June 2017 a free online *Reference Gerber Viewer* was made available by Ucamco as a complement to the specification.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] It is updated with new functionality from time to time.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] In October 2019 Ucamco published a draft specification to include component information in Gerber data, calling for comments from the user community.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] The proposal re-uses existing syntax and hence is backward compatible.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] Although it does not introduce new syntax it extends Gerber into a new domain, and the name Gerber X3 is suggested.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] The draft specification was developed by Karel Tavernier.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] Over the years there have been several attempts to replace Gerber by formats containing more information than just the layer image, e.g. netlist or component information.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] None of these attempts have been widely accepted within the electronics manufacturing industry, probably because the formats are complex.
[src:kicad-eda/gerber-format] Gerber remains the most widely used data transfer format.
[src:kicad-eda/kicad] KiCad was created in 1992 by Jean-Pierre Charras while working at IUT de Grenoble.
[src:kicad-eda/kicad] The name came from the first letters in the name of a company of Jean-Pierre's friend in combination with the term CAD.
[src:kicad-eda/kicad] KiCad originally was a collection of electronics programs intended to be used in conjunction with each other.
[src:kicad-eda/kicad] The main tools were EESchema, PCBnew, a Gerber viewer, and a calculator.
[src:kicad-eda/kicad] With the price of professionally made printed circuit boards rapidly dropping, hobbyist electronic design became much more popular.
[src:kicad-eda/kicad] As a result, KiCad started gaining significant traction and a larger developer base.
[src:kicad-eda/kicad] In 2013 the CERN BE-CO-HT section started contributing resources towards KiCad to help foster open hardware development by helping improve KiCad to be on par with commercial EDA tools.
[src:kicad-eda/kicad] From 2013 until approximately 2018 CERN provided two developers part time to help improve KiCad.
[src:kicad-eda/kicad] Much of the work provided by CERN involved massive refactoring of the code base to give KiCad a better structure to grow and adapt.
[src:kicad-eda/kicad] Help is also provided by organizing donations and fundraisers to help pay for additional contract developers for KiCad, along with sponsoring KiCad's web infrastructure.
[src:kicad-eda/kicad] Well over 1400 hours of developer time has been provided by CERN.
[src:kicad-eda/kicad] A major milestone was hit in December 2015 starting with KiCad 4.0.0, the first KiCad release adopting a point release versioning scheme.
[src:kicad-eda/kicad] This was also the first release featuring the more advanced tools implemented by CERN developers.
[src:kicad-eda/kicad] KiCad joined the Linux Foundation in November 2019.
[src:kicad-eda/kicad] Additionally two lead developers formed a services corporation in 2019 to help provide additional paid development support for KiCad.
[src:kicad-eda/kicad] KiCad uses an integrated environment for all of the stages of the design process: Schematic capture, PCB layout, Gerber file generation/visualization, and library editing.
[src:kicad-eda/kicad] KiCad is a cross-platform program, written in C++ with wxWidgets to run on FreeBSD, Linux, Microsoft Windows and Mac OS X.
[src:kicad-eda/kicad] Many component libraries are available, and users can add custom components.
[src:kicad-eda/kicad] The custom components can be available on a per-project basis or installed for use in any project.
[src:kicad-eda/kicad] There are also tools to help with importing components from other EDA applications, for instance EAGLE and Altium.
[src:kicad-eda/kicad] There are also third party libraries available for KiCad, including SnapEDA, and the Digi-Key KiCad Library.
[src:kicad-eda/kicad] Since KiCad V4 the board file is written as UTF-8-based human-readable S-expression.
[src:kicad-eda/kicad] The schematics, libraries and project files were also converted to the S-expression format in KiCad V6 for easier maintenance.
[src:kicad-eda/kicad] Configuration files are in well documented plain text as well, which helps with interfacing version control systems, as well as with automated component generation scripts.
[src:kicad-eda/kicad] Multiple languages are supported, such as Bulgarian, Catalan, Chinese, Czech, Dutch, English, Finnish, French, German, Greek, Hungarian, Italian, Japanese, Korean, Lithuanian, Polish, Portuguese, Russian, Slovak, Slovene, Spanish, and Swedish.
[src:kicad-eda/kicad] The KiCad schematic editor has features including hierarchical schematic sheets, custom symbol creation, electrical rules check (ERC) and integrated ngspice circuit simulation.
[src:kicad-eda/kicad] Schematic symbols are very loosely coupled to circuit board footprints to encourage reuse of footprints and symbols (e.g. a single 0805 footprint can be used for capacitors, resistors, inductors, etc).
[src:kicad-eda/kicad] Internally KiCad's PCB editor supports up to 32 copper layers and 32 technical layers.
[src:kicad-eda/kicad] Dimensions are stored with nanometer precision in signed 32-bit integers making the theoretical maximum PCB dimension 231 nm, or approximately 2.14 meters.
[src:kicad-eda/kicad] There are a variety of tools available while doing layout through both built in functions and external plugins.
[src:kicad-eda/kicad] Some advanced built in functionality includes a push and shove router, differential and single ended trace length tuning, net highlighting and individual layer dimming, and a highly customizable design rule checking (DRC).
[src:kicad-eda/kicad] A number of external tools have been developed following the addition of Python scripting integration in to KiCad.
[src:kicad-eda/kicad] A number of plugins exist such as a high quality silkscreen label generators, BOM and assembly viewers, panelization plugins, along with many other plugins.
[src:kicad-eda/kicad] A 3D PCB viewing function is based on STEP and VRML models, and the board model can be exported for CAD integration.
[src:kicad-eda/kicad] Alfons Wirtz's open-source Java-based FreeRouting can be used to externally autoroute boards.
[src:kicad-eda/kicad] Anthony Blake's Toporouter, a topological autorouter developed in 2008 for gEDA PCB as a Google-funded open source project mentored by DJ Delorie, has been adapted for use with KiCad as well.
[src:kicad-eda/kicad] On 12 March 2015 Olimex Ltd, a provider of development tools and embedded device programmers, announced that they have switched from EAGLE to KiCad as their primary EDA tool.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] PCBs are used to connect or "wire" components to one another in an electronic circuit.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Electrical components may be fixed to conductive pads on the outer layers, generally by soldering, which both electrically connects and mechanically fastens the components to the board.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Another manufacturing process adds vias, metal-lined drilled holes that enable electrical interconnections between conductive layers, to boards with more than a single side.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Printed circuit boards are used in nearly all electronic products today.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Alternatives to PCBs include wire wrap and point-to-point construction, both once popular but now rarely used.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] PCBs require additional design effort to lay out the circuit, but manufacturing and assembly can be automated.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Electronic design automation software is available to do much of the work of layout.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Mass-producing circuits with PCBs is cheaper and faster than with other wiring methods, as components are mounted and wired in one operation.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Large numbers of PCBs can be fabricated at the same time, and the layout has to be done only once.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] PCBs can also be made manually in small quantities, with reduced benefits.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] PCBs can be single-sided (one copper layer), double-sided (two copper layers on both sides of one substrate layer), or multi-layer (stacked layers of substrate with copper plating sandwiched between each and on the outside layers).
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Multi-layer PCBs provide much higher component density, because circuit traces on the inner layers would otherwise take up surface space between components.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] The rise in popularity of multilayer PCBs with more than two, and especially with more than four, copper planes was concurrent with the adoption of surface-mount technology.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] However, multilayer PCBs make repair, analysis, and field modification of circuits much more difficult and usually impractical.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] The world market for bare PCBs exceeded US$60.2 billion in 2014, and was estimated at $80.33 billion in 2024, forecast to be $96.57 billion for 2029, growing at 4.87% per annum.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Before the development of printed circuit boards, electrical and electronic circuits were wired point-to-point on a chassis.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Typically, the chassis was a sheet metal frame or pan, sometimes with a wooden bottom.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Components were attached to the chassis, usually by insulators when the connecting point on the chassis was metal, and then their leads were connected directly or with jumper wires by soldering, or sometimes using crimp connectors, wire connector lugs on screw terminals, or other methods.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Circuits were large, bulky, heavy, and relatively fragile (even discounting the breakable glass envelopes of the vacuum tubes that were often included in the circuits), and production was labor-intensive, so the products were expensive.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Development of the methods used in modern printed circuit boards started early in the 20th century.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] In 1903, a German inventor, Albert Hanson, described flat foil conductors laminated to an insulating board, in multiple layers.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Thomas Edison experimented with chemical methods of plating conductors onto linen paper in 1904.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Arthur Berry in 1913 patented a print-and-etch method in the UK, and in the United States Max Schoop obtained a patent to flame-spray metal onto a board through a patterned mask.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Charles Ducas in 1925 patented a method of electroplating circuit patterns.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Predating the printed circuit invention, and similar in spirit, was John Sargrove's 1936–1947 Electronic Circuit Making Equipment (ECME) that sprayed metal onto a Bakelite plastic board.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] The ECME could produce three radio boards per minute.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] The Austrian engineer Paul Eisler invented the printed circuit as part of a radio set while working in the UK around 1936.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] In 1941 a multi-layer printed circuit was used in German magnetic influence naval mines.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Around 1943 the United States began to use the technology on a large scale to make proximity fuzes for use in World War II.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Such fuzes required an electronic circuit that could withstand being fired from a gun, and could be produced in quantity.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] The Centralab Division of Globe Union submitted a proposal using thick-film technology which met the requirements.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] A ceramic plate would be screenprinted with metallic paint for conductors and carbon material for resistors, with ceramic disc capacitors and subminiature vacuum tubes soldered in place.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] The technique proved viable, and the resulting patent on the process, which was classified by the U.S.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] It was not until 1984 that the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE) awarded Harry W.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Rubinstein its Cledo Brunetti Award for early key contributions to the development of printed components and conductors on a common insulating substrate.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Rubinstein was honored in 1984 by his alma mater, the University of Wisconsin-Madison, for his innovations in the technology of printed electronic circuits and the fabrication of capacitors.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] This invention also represents a step in the development of integrated circuit technology, as not only wiring but also passive components were fabricated on the ceramic substrate.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] In 1948, the US released the invention for commercial use.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Printed circuits did not become commonplace in consumer electronics until the mid-1950s, after the *Auto-Sembly* process was developed by the United States Army.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] At around the same time in the UK work along similar lines was carried out by Geoffrey Dummer, then at the RRDE.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Motorola was an early leader in bringing the process into consumer electronics, announcing in August 1952 the adoption of "plated circuits" in home radios after six years of research and a $1M investment.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Motorola soon began using its trademarked term for the process, PLAcir, in its consumer radio advertisements.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Hallicrafters released its first "foto-etch" printed circuit product, a clock-radio, on November 1, 1952.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Even as circuit boards became available, the point-to-point chassis construction method remained in common use in industry (such as TV and hi-fi sets) into at least the late 1960s.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Printed circuit boards were introduced to reduce the size, weight, and cost of parts of the circuitry.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] In 1960, a small consumer radio receiver might be built with all its circuitry on one circuit board, but a TV set would probably contain one or more circuit boards.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Originally, every electronic component had wire leads, and a PCB had holes drilled for each wire of each component.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] The component leads were then inserted through the holes and soldered to the copper PCB traces.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] This method of assembly is called *through-hole* construction.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Danko of the United States Army Signal Corps developed the *Auto-Sembly* process in which component leads were inserted into a copper foil interconnection pattern and dip soldered.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] The patent they obtained in 1956 was assigned to the U.S.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] With the development of board lamination and etching techniques, this concept evolved into the standard printed circuit board fabrication process in use today.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Soldering could be done automatically by passing the board over a ripple, or wave, of molten solder in a wave-soldering machine.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] However, the wires and holes are inefficient since drilling holes is expensive and consumes drill bits and the protruding wires are cut off and discarded.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Since the 1980s, surface mount parts have increasingly replaced through-hole components, enabling smaller boards and lower production costs, but making repairs more challenging.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] In the 1990s the use of multilayer surface boards became more frequent.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] As a result, size was further minimized and both flexible and rigid PCBs were incorporated in different devices.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] In 1995 PCB manufacturers began using microvia technology to produce High-Density Interconnect (HDI) PCBs.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Recent advances in 3D printing have meant that there are several new techniques in PCB creation.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] 3D printed electronics (PEs) can be utilized to print items layer by layer and subsequently the item can be printed with a liquid ink that contains electronic functionalities.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] HDI (High Density Interconnect) technology allows for a denser design on the PCB and thus potentially smaller PCBs with more traces and components in a given area.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] As a result, the paths between components can be shorter.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] HDIs use blind/buried vias, or a combination that includes microvias.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] With multi-layer HDI PCBs the interconnection of several vias stacked on top of each other (stacked vías, instead of one deep buried via) can be made stronger, thus enhancing reliability in all conditions.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] The most common applications for HDI technology are computer and mobile phone components as well as medical equipment and military communication equipment.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] A 4-layer HDI microvia PCB is equivalent in quality to an 8-layer through-hole PCB, so HDI technology can reduce costs.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] HDI PCBs are often made using build-up film such as ajinomoto build-up film, which is also used in the production of flip chip packages.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Some PCBs have optical waveguides, similar to optical fibers built on the PCB.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] A basic PCB consists of a flat sheet of insulating material and a layer of copper foil, laminated to the substrate.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Chemical etching divides the copper into separate conducting lines called tracks or *circuit traces*, pads for connections, vias to pass connections between layers of copper, and features such as solid conductive areas for electromagnetic shielding or other purposes.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] The tracks function as wires fixed in place, and are insulated from each other by air and the board substrate material.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] The surface of a PCB may have a coating that protects the copper from corrosion and reduces the chances of solder shorts between traces or undesired electrical contact with stray bare wires.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] For its function in helping to prevent solder shorts, the coating is called solder resist or solder mask.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] The pattern to be etched into each copper layer of a PCB is called the "artwork".
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] The etching is usually done using photoresist which is coated onto the PCB, then exposed to light projected in the pattern of the artwork.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] The resist material protects the copper from dissolution into the etching solution.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] A PCB design can be mass-reproduced in a way similar to the way photographs can be mass-duplicated from film negatives using a photographic printer.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] FR-4 glass epoxy is the most common insulating substrate.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Another substrate material is cotton paper impregnated with phenolic resin, often tan or brown.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] A PCB may be printed with a legend identifying the components, test points, or identifying text.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Originally, silkscreen printing was used for this purpose, but today other, finer quality printing methods are usually used.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Normally the legend does not affect the function of a PCBA.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] A printed circuit board can have multiple layers of copper which almost always are arranged in pairs.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] The number of layers and the interconnection designed between them (vias, PTHs) provide a general estimate of the board complexity.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Using more layers allow for more routing options and better control of signal integrity, but are also time-consuming and costly to manufacture.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Likewise, selection of the vias for the board also allow fine tuning of the board size, escaping of signals off complex ICs, routing, and long term reliability, but are tightly coupled with production complexity and cost.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] One of the simplest boards to produce is the two-layer board.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] It has copper on both sides that are referred to as external layers; multi layer boards sandwich additional internal layers of copper and insulation.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] After two-layer PCBs, the next step up is the four-layer.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Only the outer layers need be coated; the inner copper layers are protected by the adjacent substrate layers.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] "Through hole" components are mounted by their wire leads passing through the board and soldered to traces on the other side.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] "Surface mount" components are attached by their leads to copper traces on the same side of the board.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] A board may use both methods for mounting components.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] PCBs with only through-hole mounted components are now uncommon.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Surface mounting is used for transistors, diodes, IC chips, resistors, and capacitors.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Through-hole mounting may be used for some large components such as electrolytic capacitors and connectors.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] The first PCBs used through-hole technology, mounting electronic components by inserting leads through holes on one side of the board and soldering onto copper traces on the other side.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Boards may be single-sided, with an unplated component side, or more compact double-sided boards, with components soldered on both sides.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Leads may be soldered either manually or by a wave soldering machine.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Surface-mount technology emerged in the 1960s, gained momentum in the early 1980s, and became widely used by the mid-1990s.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Components were mechanically redesigned to have small metal tabs or end caps that could be soldered directly onto the PCB surface, instead of wire leads to pass through holes.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Components became much smaller and component placement on both sides of the board became more common than with through-hole mounting, allowing much smaller PCB assemblies with much higher circuit densities.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Surface mounting lends itself well to a high degree of automation, reducing labor costs and greatly increasing production rates compared with through-hole circuit boards.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Components can be supplied mounted on carrier tapes.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Surface mount components can be about one-quarter to one-tenth of the size and weight of through-hole components, and passive components much cheaper.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] However, prices of semiconductor surface mount devices (SMDs) are determined more by the chip itself than the package, with little price advantage over larger packages, and some wire-ended components, such as 1N4148 small-signal switch diodes, are actually significantly cheaper than SMD equivalents.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Each trace consists of a flat, narrow part of the copper foil that remains after etching.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Its resistance, determined by its width, thickness, and length, must be sufficiently low for the current the conductor will carry.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Power and ground traces may need to be wider than signal traces.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] In a multi-layer board one entire layer may be mostly solid copper to act as a ground plane for shielding and power return.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] For microwave circuits and high-speed digital signals (which use similar frequencies), transmission lines can be laid out in a planar form such as stripline or microstrip with carefully controlled dimensions to assure a consistent impedance.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] High density interconnects (HDI) PCBs have tracks or vias with a width or diameter of under 152 micrometers.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Laminates are manufactured by curing layers of cloth or paper with thermoset resin under pressure and heat to form an integral final piece of uniform thickness.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] They can be up to 4 by 8 feet (1.2 by 2.4 m) in width and length.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Varying cloth weaves (threads per inch or cm), cloth thickness, and resin percentage are used to achieve the desired final thickness and dielectric characteristics.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Available standard laminate thickness are listed in ANSI/IPC-D-275.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] The cloth or fiber material used, resin material, and the cloth to resin ratio determine the laminate's type designation (FR-4, CEM-1, G-10, etc.) and therefore the characteristics of the laminate produced.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] There are quite a few different dielectrics that can be chosen to provide different insulating values depending on the requirements of the circuit.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Some of these dielectrics are polytetrafluoroethylene (Teflon), FR-4, FR-1, CEM-1 or CEM-3.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Thermal expansion is an important consideration especially with ball grid array (BGA) and naked die technologies, and glass fiber offers the best dimensional stability.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] FR-4 is by far the most common material used today.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] The board stock with unetched copper on it is called "copper-clad laminate".
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] With decreasing size of board features and increasing frequencies, small non-homogeneities like uneven distribution of fiberglass or other filler, thickness variations, and bubbles in the resin matrix, and the associated local variations in the dielectric constant, are gaining importance.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] The circuit-board substrates are usually dielectric composite materials.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] The composites contain a matrix (usually an epoxy resin) and a reinforcement (usually a woven, sometimes non-woven, glass fibers, sometimes even paper), and in some cases a filler is added to the resin (e.g. ceramics; titanate ceramics can be used to increase the dielectric constant).
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] The reinforcement type defines two major classes of materials: woven and non-woven.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Woven reinforcements are cheaper, but the high dielectric constant of glass may not be favorable for many higher-frequency applications.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] The spatially non-homogeneous structure also introduces local variations in electrical parameters, due to different resin/glass ratio at different areas of the weave pattern.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Non-woven reinforcements, or materials with low or no reinforcement, are more expensive but more suitable for some RF/analog applications.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] At the glass transition temperature the resin in the composite softens and significantly increases thermal expansion; exceeding Tg then exerts mechanical overload on the board components - e.g. the joints and the vias.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Below Tg the thermal expansion of the resin roughly matches copper and glass, above it gets significantly higher.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] As the reinforcement and copper confine the board along the plane, virtually all volume expansion projects to the thickness and stresses the plated-through holes.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Repeated soldering or other exposition to higher temperatures can cause failure of the plating, especially with thicker boards; thick boards therefore require a matrix with a high Tg.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] The materials used determine the substrate's dielectric constant.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] This constant is also dependent on frequency, usually decreasing with frequency.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] As this constant determines the signal propagation speed, frequency dependence introduces phase distortion in wideband applications; as flat a dielectric constant vs frequency characteristics as is achievable is important here.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] The impedance of transmission lines decreases with frequency, therefore faster edges of signals reflect more than slower ones.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Dielectric breakdown voltage determines the maximum voltage gradient the material can be subjected to before suffering a breakdown (conduction, or arcing, through the dielectric).
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Tracking resistance determines how the material resists high voltage electrical discharges creeping over the board surface.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Loss tangent determines how much of the electromagnetic energy from the signals in the conductors is absorbed in the board material.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] This factor is important for high frequencies.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Choosing unnecessarily low-loss material is a common engineering error in high-frequency digital design; it increases the cost of the boards without a corresponding benefit.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Signal degradation by loss tangent and dielectric constant can be easily assessed by an eye pattern.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Moisture absorption occurs when the material is exposed to high humidity or water.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Both the resin and the reinforcement may absorb water; water also may be soaked by capillary forces through voids in the materials and along the reinforcement.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Epoxies of the FR-4 materials are not too susceptible, with absorption of only 0.15%.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Teflon has very low absorption of 0.01%.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Polyimides and cyanate esters, on the other side, suffer from high water absorption.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Absorbed water can lead to significant degradation of key parameters; it impairs tracking resistance, breakdown voltage, and dielectric parameters.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Relative dielectric constant of water is about 73, compared to about 4 for common circuit board materials.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Absorbed moisture can also vaporize on heating, as during soldering, and cause cracking and delamination, the same effect responsible for "popcorning" damage on wet packaging of electronic parts.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Careful baking of the substrates may be required to dry them prior to soldering.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Copper thickness of PCBs can be specified directly or as the weight of copper per area (in ounce per square foot) which is easier to measure.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] One ounce per square foot is 34 μm (0.0013 in) thickness.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] *Heavy copper* is a layer exceeding three ounces of copper per ft2, or approximately 105 μm (0.0041 in) thick.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Heavy copper layers are used for high current or to help dissipate heat.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] On the common FR-4 substrates, 1 oz copper per ft2 (35 μm (0.0014 in)) is the most common thickness; 2 oz (70 μm (0.0028 in)) and 0.5 oz (17.5 μm (0.00069 in)) thickness is often an option.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Flexible substrates typically have thinner metalization.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Metal-core boards for high power devices commonly use thicker copper; 35 μm (0.0014 in) is usual but also 140 μm (0.0055 in) and 400 μm (0.016 in) can be encountered.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] In the US, copper foil thickness is specified in units of ounces per square foot (oz/ft2), commonly referred to simply as *ounce*.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] 1/2 oz/ft2 foil is not widely used as a finished copper weight, but is used for outer layers when plating for through holes will increase the finished copper weight.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Some PCB manufacturers refer to 1 oz/ft2 copper foil as having a thickness of 35 μm (0.0014 in) (may also be referred to as 35 μ, 35 micron, or 35 mic).
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Printed circuit board manufacturing involves manufacturing bare printed circuit boards and then populating them with electronic components.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] In large-scale board manufacturing, multiple PCBs are grouped on a single panel for efficient processing.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] After assembly, they are separated (depaneled).
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] A minimal PCB for a single component, used for prototyping, is called a **breakout board**.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] The purpose of a breakout board is to "break out" the leads of a component on separate terminals so that manual connections to them can be made easily.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Breakout boards are especially used for surface-mount components or any components with fine lead pitch.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Advanced PCBs may contain components embedded in the substrate, such as capacitors and integrated circuits, to reduce the amount of space taken up by components on the surface of the PCB while improving electrical characteristics.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Multiwire is a patented technique of interconnection which uses machine-routed insulated wires embedded in a non-conducting matrix (often plastic resin).
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] As of 2010, Multiwire is still available through Hitachi.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Corrections can be made to a Multiwire board layout more easily than to a PCB layout.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Before the advent of integrated circuits, *cordwood construction* allowed the highest possible component packing density.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] The construction method was used with wire-ended components in applications where space was at a premium (such as fuzes, missile guidance, and telemetry systems) and in the high-speed computers of the day, where short traces were important.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] In cordwood construction, axial-leaded components were mounted between two parallel planes.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] The name comes from the way axial-lead components (capacitors, resistors, coils, and diodes) are stacked in parallel rows and columns, like a stack of firewood.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] The components were either soldered together with jumper wire or they were connected to other components by thin nickel ribbon welded at right angles onto the component leads.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Some versions of cordwood construction used soldered single-sided PCBs as the interconnection method (as pictured), allowing the use of normal-leaded components at the cost of being difficult to remove the boards or replace any component that is not at the edge.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Cordwood construction was replaced with multi-layer board, SMD and ICs.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] A **Flexible Printed Circuit Board (FPCB)** is a thin, lightweight circuit made from flexible materials like polyimide.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] It can bend or fold while maintaining reliable electrical connections and is commonly used in compact electronic devices such as smartphones, wearables, and medical equipment.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Printed circuit boards have been used as an alternative to their typical use for electronic and biomedical engineering thanks to the versatility of their layers, especially the copper layer.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Manufacturers may not support component-level repair of printed circuit boards because of the relatively low cost to replace compared with the time and cost of troubleshooting to a component level.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] In board-level repair, the technician identifies the board (PCA) on which the fault resides and replaces it.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] In many countries (including all European Single Market participants, the United Kingdom, Turkey, and China), legislation restricts the use of lead, cadmium, and mercury in electrical equipment.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] PCBs sold in such countries must therefore use lead-free manufacturing processes and lead-free solder, and attached components must themselves be compliant.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Safety Standard UL 796 covers component safety requirements for printed wiring boards for use as components in devices or appliances.
[src:kicad-eda/printed-circuit-board] Testing analyzes characteristics such as flammability, maximum operating temperature, electrical tracking, heat deflection, and direct support of live electrical parts.
[src:kicad-eda/schematic-capture] The circuit design is the first step of actual design of an electronic circuit.
[src:kicad-eda/schematic-capture] Typically sketches are drawn on paper, and then entered into a computer using a schematic editor.
[src:kicad-eda/schematic-capture] Therefore schematic entry is said to be a front-end operation of several others in the design flow.
[src:kicad-eda/schematic-capture] Despite the complexity of modern components – huge ball grid arrays and tiny passive components – schematic capture is easier today than it has been for many years.
[src:kicad-eda/schematic-capture] CAD software is easier to use and is available in full-featured expensive packages, very capable mid-range packages that sometimes have free versions and completely free versions that are either open source or directly linked to a printed circuit board fabrication company.
[src:kicad-eda/schematic-capture] In past years, schematic diagrams with mostly discrete components were fairly readable.
[src:kicad-eda/schematic-capture] However, with the newer high pin-count parts and with the almost universal use of standard letter- or A4-sized paper, schematics have become less so.
[src:kicad-eda/schematic-capture] Many times, there will be a single large part on a page with nothing but pin reference keys to connect it to other pages.
[src:kicad-eda/schematic-capture] Readability levels can be enhanced by using buses and superbuses, related pins can be connected into a common bus and routed to other pages.
[src:kicad-eda/schematic-capture] Buses don't need to be just the traditional address or data bus directly linked pins.
[src:kicad-eda/schematic-capture] A bus grouping can also be used for related uses, such as all analog input or all communications related pin functions.
[src:kicad-eda/schematic-capture] After the circuit design is captured in a schematic, most EDA tools allow the design to be simulated.
[src:kicad-eda/schematic-capture] Schematic capture involves not only entering the circuits into the CAD system, but also generally calls for decisions that may seem more appropriate for later in the design, such as package choice.
[src:kicad-eda/schematic-capture] Although you may be able to change the package later, many PCB CAD systems ask you to choose both the part and package when placing it into the schematic capture program.
[src:kicad-eda/schematic-capture] This also brings into play such considerations as prototyping and assembly.
[src:kicad-eda/schematic-capture] In a high-volume assembly environment, there will be plenty of opportunities for DFM analysis.
[src:kicad-eda/schematic-capture] However, in a rapid prototyping environment such as at assembly houses specializing in low-volume/high-mix and quick turnaround times, the pick and place machines are programmed directly from the board layout files.
[src:kicad-eda/schematic-capture] Careful package selection during schematic capture will save time during the assembly and debug process.
[src:kicad-eda/schematic-capture] With new parts, the CAD system may not have your chosen component in its parts library, so you may need to create the parts library yourself.
[src:kicad-eda/schematic-capture] Again, you may at the time not be overly concerned with the package, but careful creation of the part library will save time and risk later.
